06218nam a22010215i 9780520917033DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20202023cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209170337 a10.1525/97805209170332doi  a(DE-B1597)544129  a(OCoLC)1149512144  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aGF532.P4bZ56 1996eb 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a306.3/49/0985372201 aZimmerer, Karl S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aChanging Fortunes :bBiodiversity and Peasant Livelihood in the Peruvian Andes /cKarl S. Zimmerer.  aReprint 2019 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2020] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (309 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCalifornia Studies in Critical Human Geography ;v100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Fields of Plenty and Want -- t2. The Great Historical Arch of Andean Biodiversity -- t3. Transitions in Farm Nature and Society, 1969-1990 -- t4. Innovation and the Spaces of Biodiversity -- t5. Loss and Conservation of the Diverse Crops -- t6. Diversity’s Sum: Geography, Ecology- Economy, and Culture -- t7. The Vicissitudes of Biodiversity’s Fortune -- tAppendix A. Common Explanations of Genetic Erosion -- tAppendix B. Crop Biogeography and Vegetation in Paucartambo -- tAppendix C. The Human Geography of Agriculture in the Paucartambo Andes -- tAppendix D. Production Techniques and Farm Spaces in Paucartambo -- tAppendix E. Cultural Attributes of the Diverse Crops in Paucartambo -- tAppendix F. Farm Management of the Diverse Crops -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTwo of the world's most pressing needs—biodiversity conservation and agricultural development in the Third World—are addressed in Karl S. Zimmerer's multidisciplinary investigation in geography. Zimmerer challenges current opinion by showing that the world-renowned diversity of crops grown in the Andes may not be as hopelessly endangered as is widely believed. He uses the lengthy history of small-scale farming by Indians in Peru, including contemporary practices and attitudes, to shed light on prospects for the future. During prolonged fieldwork among Peru's Quechua peasants and villagers in the mountains near Cuzco, Zimmerer found convincing evidence that much of the region's biodiversity is being skillfully conserved on a de facto basis, as has been true during centuries of tumultuous agrarian transitions.Diversity occurs unevenly, however, because of the inability of poorer Quechua farmers to plant the same variety as their well-off neighbors and because land use pressures differ in different locations. Social, political, and economic upheavals have accentuated the unevenness, and Zimmerer's geographical findings are all the more important as a result. Diversity is indeed at serious risk, but not necessarily for the same reasons that have been cited by others. The originality of this study is in its correlation of ecological conservation, ethnic expression, and economic development.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAgriculture and statezPeruzPaucartambo (Province). 0aAgriculture and state. 0aAgriculturexSocial aspectszPeruzPaucartambo (Province). 0aAgriculture. 0aBiodiversityzPeruzPaucartambo (Province)xSocial conditions. 0aBiodiversityzPeruzPaucartambo (Province). 0aConservation of natural resourcesxSocial aspectszPeruzPaucartambo (Province). 0aConservation of natural resourceszPeruzPaucartambo (Province). 0aHuman ecologyxAgriculturezPeruzPaucartambo (Province). 0aHuman ecologyzPeruzPaucartambo (Province). 0aQuechua IndiansxAgriculture. 0aQuechua IndiansxSocial conditions. 0aQu